title.narrative: Turkey as an emerging humanitarian donor

description.narrative: • Over the past several years, various discussions on Turkey and how to engage with it have taken place within Oxfam informed by developments in Turkey over the last decade that created a perception of the country as an emerging power, a new player in international development aid and humanitarian assistance. With an economy that is now the world’s 18th largest, Turkey is considered an upper middle-income country by the World Bank, and is a member of the G20. Although it is itself still an aid recipient, Turkey’s international development aid has increased from USD120 million in 1999 to an estimated USD1.3 billion in 2011. • Turkey was the 4th largestdonor of humanitarian assistance across the world in 2012, contributing over one billion USD. With this, its International development assistance surpassed USD 2,5 billion in the same year. Turkey is aiming to reach USD 5 billion in international development assistance by 2015 and USD 10 billion by 2020. Reaching such targets will put Turkey in the ranks of the world’s major donors, ranking it the 9th largest DAC donor by 2015, and the 6th largest by 2020 (Turkey is not yet a DAC member, though it has been invited to join the DAC). • The importance of engaging with Turkey has resonated within Oxfam linked to this increasing influence of Turkey especially in Middle East and Africa, its multi-polar engagement, and the geographical and financial expansion of its development and humanitarian aid. Oxfam’s aim to influence the international aid landscape towards an equitable development that prioritizes poverty reduction and equal access to services and opportunities demands a comprehensive understanding of the profusion of donors, the emerging models of development, their impact on conventional models as well as on developing countries, and the possible "tug-of-war "thatis likely to emerge among donors. • A fast response by Oxfam to this emerging situation through not only expansion of coverage but also proper investment in policy research has the potential to position Oxfam as one of the important institutions that can help mediate the tensions between aid modalities for the benefit of the disadvantaged and excluded. • Against this background, ONL started to explore ways of engagement with Turkey as a regional and global actor, initially through series of consultations with relevant civil society and government agencies. Conversations took place with Turkish national civil society organisations to identify potentialissues for joint programming on the role of Turkey as an emerging power. Since March 2013 ONL has based a senior policy officer in Istanbul, Turkey to follow up on initial ideas and conversations in relation to Turkey’s emerging role as a regional and global actor, to identify further entry points and to build relations that could pave the road for establishment of an Oxfam International Advocacy Office in Turkey.

participating-org.narrative: Oxfam Novib was founded in 1956 as the Netherlands Organisation for International Assistance (Novib), and joined forces with Oxfam in 1994. Oxfam Novib is member of the Oxfam International confederation. Working together in the confederation, the Oxfam affiliates can speak with one clear and compelling voice on issues of global concern: climate change, health and education for all, agriculture, trade, and conflicts and emergencies. Oxfam Novib's main office is based in The Netherlands, it supports the work of a network of local offices, the implementation of global projects, fundraising, campaigning and advocacy. Oxfam Novib’s the Hague office contributes towards this project’s implementation.
